Starting April 7th, in Minsk, Belarus the reception of visitors in hairdressing salons, tattoo parlors, beauty salons, permanent make-up salons and other similar locations in the beauty industry should be carried out only by appointment with an interval between clients of at least 5 minutes and with personnel subject to a mask regimen.

On April 7th in Minsk, Belarus, it is announced that organizations of all forms of ownership in premises with workers staying, are required to ensure: wet cleaning with detergents and disinfectants, effective operation of ventilation and air conditioning systems in compliance with indoor climate conditions, and preventing unauthorized persons from visiting the premises of organizations. They must also limit the number of workers per shift, splitting up their flows in the case of two or three shifts and providing for a break that lasts at least 30 minutes.

Since June 5th, intervals of public transport have been decreased during rush hours in Minsk, Belarus. In the morning rush hours, the number of buses on routes No. 115E, 127, 144C, 159 was increased by 1 unit per each, from 6:30 to 8:30 and from 17:00 to 19:00 the interval of train traffic was reduced from 3 minutes to 2.5 minutes on both the first and second line of the metro line.

Starting on June 13th, the subway train interval will be reduced by one minute on weekends in Minsk, Belarus. As such, more trains will go on both lines of the subway from 7:00 to 20:00 every weekend and as necessary, rolling stock will be added to certain routes. Currently, the interval of train traffic in the specified period is from 5 to 6 minutes on the 1st line on Saturday and from 6.5 to 7.5 minutes on Sunday; on the 2nd line - from 6 to 6.5 minutes on Saturday and from 6.5 to 7 minutes on Sunday.
